<DOC><DOCNO> AP880412-0237 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-88 0056EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-12 0501</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0523</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil prices have leaped to the highest level ofthe year, partly reflecting speculation that OPEC would be able torecruit help from outside producers to constrict world supplies.   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May-delivery contractfor West Texas Intermediate crude oil jumped $1.01 per barrel onMonday to $17.89, the highest level since a closing of $17.85reached Jan. 5. It was one of the biggest one-day moves ever,traders said.   Some traders and analysts said the gain was not sustainable. Butothers said it signaled a more fundamental change in marketsentiment that indicated the end of a low-price era in thepetroleum business.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Reagan administration has indicated theworld's top industrial countries are near agreement on a proposalto use the price of gold and other commodities to help in theinternational coordination of exchange rates.   The disclosure Monday came as representatives of the 151-nationInternational Monetary Fund and the World Bank began five days ofhigh-level meetings with exchange rates, trade issues and ThirdWorld debt dominating the agenda.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Odyssey Partners is keeping the heat on in thecontest for control of J.P. Stevens andamp; Co.   Odyssey increased its buyout price for the textile giant to$1.22 billion Monday, hours after rival suitor West Point-PepperellInc. raised its bid to $1.19 billion.   Stevens indicated its prior agreement to merge with Odysseywould remain in effect under the higher offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. plans to sell itsconsumer finance unit for $685 million in cash to a unit ofAmerican General Corp., a Texas-based financial service concern.   The companies said Monday they reached an agreement in principleon the sale of Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services Inc. in adeal that would nearly double the size of American General'sconsumer credit operations.</TEXT><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A.H. Robins Co. has told a federal judgehis decision to set $2.475 billion in compensation for DalkonShield victims helped kill a pending buyout of the pharmaceuticalcompany.   But a lawyer for Rorer Group Inc., which planned to acquireRobins, told U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. on Mondaythat the judge's ruling did not automatically destroy Robins' pactwith Rorer.   Merhige and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley listenedto arguments on whether Robins should pay a $25 million``break-up'' fee to Rorer plus $9 million in expenses associatedwith the failed merger.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Trade Commission has revived acomplaint that an R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. advertisement in 1985misrepresented the results of a government study on the effects ofsmoking on health.   In a 4-1 vote Monday, the commission reversed a ruling made lastAugust by an administrative law judge who had dismissed thecomplaint on grounds that the ad was an editorial and therefore wasprotected by First Amendment guarantees on freedom of speech.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>